THIS FILE IS NOT LEGAL ADVICE.
READ THE LINKED OFFICIAL PAGES FROM CREATIVECOMMONS IF
YOU WANT TO BE SURE THAT YOU HAVE THE RIGHT INFORMATION!

All of the files in this repository that do not explicitly specify a
different license are free to reuse under the terms of CC BY-SA 4.0.

For details from the fine folks who wrote the license, visit this page:
  > https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/

Basically, that means you are free to use, distribute, and modify most of
our video scripts for any purpose, even commerically, as long as you:

1/4 ...credit us.
    A generic attribution you can just copy and paste should
    be included at the top of each file.

    However, it is okay to credit us differently.
    The information you should usually include is explained on this page:
  > https://wiki.creativecommons.org/wiki/Recommended_practices_for_attribution

    Basically, it says you should include "TASL," which stands for:
  - TITLE
    ...is the title of the file, if it has one (it definitely does in our case).
  - AUTHOR
    ...is the file's creator or copyright holder.
  - SOURCE: 
    ...is a way for someone to find the file. Usually, this would be a link.
  - LICENSE
    ...is the file's license (usually CC BY-SA 4.0 in our case).
    You should, but don't absolutely have to, include a link to the license.

2/4 ...distribute your copies and derivatives of
    them under the same license or a compatible one.

    This page explains what licenses you can use (scroll down to BY-SA -> 4.0):
  > https://creativecommons.org/share-your-work/licensing-considerations/compatible-licenses/

    As of 2024-04-23, the officially approved ones are:
  - CC BY-SA 4.0 or later
  - Free Art License 1.3
  - GNU General Public License version 3

    This page has a table showing how works using different
    CreativeCommons licenses can officially be combined:
  > https://wiki.creativecommons.org/wiki/Wiki/cc_license_compatibility

3/4 ...state what changes you have made.

4/4 ...do not implement any legal or technical measures to
    prevent recipients from doing something the license permits.
